<h3>Secant method</h3>
<p>The secant method can be thought of as a finite difference approximation=
 of Newton's method, where a derivative is replaced by a secant line.</p>
<p>We use the root of a secant line (the value of x such that y=3D0) as a r=
oot approximation for function f.</p>
<p>Suppose we have starting values x0 and x1, with function values f(x0) an=
d f(x1).<br>
The secant line has the equation </p>
<p><img src=3D"https://planetcalc.com/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?%5Cfrac%7By%20-%2=
0f%28x_1%29%7D%7Bf%28x_1%29-f%28x_0%29%7D%3D%5Cfrac%7Bx%20-%20x_1%7D%7Bx_1-=
x_0%7D" alt=3D"\frac{y - f(x_1)}{f(x_1)-f(x_0)}=3D\frac{x - x_1}{x_1-x_0}" =
class=3D"pc-math"></p>
<p>Hence, the root of secant line (where =D1=83=3D0) is</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://planetcalc.com/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x%20%3D%20x_1%20-=
%20%5Cfrac%7Bx_1%20-%20x_0%7D%7Bf%28x_1%29-f%28x_0%29%7Df%28x_1%29" alt=3D"=
x =3D x_1 - \frac{x_1 - x_0}{f(x_1)-f(x_0)}f(x_1)" class=3D"pc-math"></p>
<p>This is a recurrence relation for the secant method. A graphical interpr=
etation can be seen below.</p>
<p></p><div style=3D"text-align:center"><img class=3D"je" src=3D"https://pl=
anetcalc.com/users/2/1403376714.png" alt=3D"640px_1.png" title=3D"640px_1.p=
ng"></div><p></p>
<p><a href=3D"http://ru.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D0%A4%D0%B0%D0%B9%D0%BB:%D0%9C%=
D0%B5%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%B4_%D1%85%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%B4_%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%811.png" r=
el=3D"nofollow">Source</a></p>
<p>The secant method does not require that the root remains bracketed like =
the bisection method does (see below), and hence it does not always converg=
e.</p>
<p></p><div style=3D"text-align:center"><img class=3D"je" src=3D"https://pl=
anetcalc.com/users/2/1403376724.png" alt=3D"640px_2.png" title=3D"640px_2.p=
ng"></div><p></p>
<p><a href=3D"http://ru.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D0%A4%D0%B0%D0%B9%D0%BB:%D0%9C%=
D0%B5%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%B4_%D1%85%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%B4_%D1%80%D0%B8%D1%812.png" r=
el=3D"nofollow">Source</a></p>
<p>As can be seen from the recurrence relation, the secant method requires =
two initial values, x0 and x1, which should ideally be chosen to lie close =
to the root.</p>
<p>The tolerance condition can be either:</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://planetcalc.com/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?f%28x_k%29%26lt%3=
B%20%5Cepsilon" alt=3D"f(x_k)&lt; \epsilon" class=3D"pc-math"> =E2=80=94 fu=
nction value is less than =CE=B5.</p>
<p><img src=3D"https://planetcalc.com/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?%5Cleft%7Cx_k-x_%=
7Bk-1%7D%5Cright%7C%20%26lt%3B%20%5Cepsilon" alt=3D"\left|x_k-x_{k-1}\right=
| &lt; \epsilon" class=3D"pc-math"> =E2=80=94 the difference between two su=
bsequent =D1=85k is less than  =CE=B5.</p>
<p>More: <a href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secant_method" rel=3D"nofo=
llow">Secant method</a></p></div></div><div id=3D"copied_msg" class=3D"ke">=
